Chi_Square_Normal_Test <- function(x, n) {
   break_p <- vector("double", length = n + 1)
   x_mean <- mean(x)
   x_stdev <- sqrt(var(x))
   break_p[1] <- min(x) - 1
   size <- length(x)
   for(j in 2:n) {
      break_p[j] <- qnorm((j-1)/n, mean = x_mean, 
      sd = x_stdev, lower.tail = TRUE, log.p = FALSE)
      }
   break_p[n+1] <- max(x) + 1
   p_x <- hist(x, breaks = break_p, plot = FALSE)
   x_Counts <- p_x$counts
   Norm_counts <- vector("double", length = n)
   for(j in 1:n) {
      Norm_counts[j] <- size * 1/n
      }
   p_SE <- hist(x, breaks = break_p, main="Histogram of 
   Standardized Errors")
   normal_fit <- chisq.test(x_Counts, p = Norm_counts,
   rescale.p = TRUE)
   Chitest_value <- pchisq(normal_fit$statistic, df = n - 3, 
   lower.tail=FALSE)
   return(Chitest_value)
}
standarized_errors_MR <- function(y, x) {
   n <- length(y)
   k <- ncol(x)
   x1 <- vector("double", length = n)
   for(j in 1:n) {
      x1[j] <- 1
      }
   Matrix_X <- cbind(x1, x)
   Matrix_Y <- cbind(y)
   Matrix_H <- Matrix_X%*%solve(t(Matrix_X)%*%Matrix_X)%*%t(Matrix_X)
   Matrix_YP <- Matrix_H%*%Matrix_Y
   y_p <- Matrix_YP[,1]
   h <- vector("double", length = n)
   D <- vector("double", length = n)
   Error <- vector("double", length = n)
   Standard_E <- vector("double", length = n)
   se <- sqrt(sum((y - y_p)^2)/(n - k - 1))
   for(i in 1:n) {
      h[i] <- Matrix_H[i,i]
      Error[i] <- y[i] - y_p[i]
      Standard_E[i] <- Error[i] / (se * sqrt(1 - h[i]))
      D[i] <- (y[i] - y_p[i])^2 * h[i] / ((k - 1) * se^2 * (1 - h[i])^2)
      }
    SEhD <- cbind(Standard_E,h,D)
   return(SEhD)}
Run_Test <- function(x) {
    size <- length(x)
  Run_Count <- vector("double", length = size)
  x_median <- median(x)
    x_cat <- x > x_median
    print(x_cat)
    Run_Count[1] <- 1
    for(j in 2:n) {
    if (x_cat[j] == x_cat[j-1]) {
      Run_Count[j] <- Run_Count[j-1]
  } else {
      Run_Count[j] <- Run_Count[j-1] + 1
          } 
    }
    n1 <- sum(x_cat == 'TRUE')
    n2 <- sum(x_cat == 'FALSE')
    Run_Mean <- 2*n1*n2/(n1+n2) + 1
    Run_S <- sqrt(2*n1*n2*(2*n1*n2-n1-n2)/(n1+n2)^2/(n1+n2-1))
    Run_Z = (Run_Count[size] - Run_Mean) / Run_S
    if (Run_Z < 0) {
      Run_Pvalue <- pnorm(Run_Count[size], mean=Run_Mean, sd=Run_S, lower.tail=TRUE)*2
  } else {
      Run_Pvalue <- pnorm(Run_Count[size], mean=Run_Mean, sd=Run_S, lower.tail=FALSE)*2
          } 
    Run_Return_V <- vector("double", length = 7)
    Run_Return_V[1] <- n1
    Run_Return_V[2] <- n2
    Run_Return_V[3] <- Run_Count[size]
    Run_Return_V[4] <- Run_Mean
    Run_Return_V[5] <- Run_S
    Run_Return_V[6] <- Run_Z
    Run_Return_V[7] <- Run_Pvalue
    return(Run_Return_V)
}
Hetero_plot <- function(y,x,l)
{
  n <- length(y)
  linearModelVar <- lm(y ~ x)
  a <- coef(linearModelVar)[1]
  b = vector("numeric",l)
  for(i in 1:l)
  {
    b[i] <- coef(linearModelVar)[i+1]
  }
  Price_p <- vector("double", length = n)
  for(i in 1:n) {
    temp = a
    for(j in 1:l)
      temp = temp + b[j]*x[i,j]
    Price_p[i] <- temp
  }
  Standard_E <- standarized_errors_MR(y,x)[,1]
  plot(x = Price_p,y = Standard_E,  xlab = "Predicted Price",  ylab = "Standardized Error",  xlim = c(min(Price_p)-0.1,max(Price_p)+0.1),  ylim = c(-3,3), main = "y vs Error")

}

2. Propose a statistical model

Suppose that demand of drywall is related to the number of permits (x1), the Five-year mortgage rates (x2), the Vacancy rate in apartments (x3) and the Vacancy rate in office buildings(x4) and the error\(\epsilon\) by the following regression model: \[y = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \beta_2x_2 + \beta_3x_3 + \beta_4x_4 + \epsilon \] where y = demand of drywall), x1= the number of permits, x2= the Five-year mortgage rates, x3= the Vacancy rate in apartments, x4= the Vacancy rate in office buildings. ε = error variable.

6. Interpretation

\(\beta_0\):This is the intercept, the value of y when all the variables take the value zero. Since the data range of all the independent variables do not cover the value zero, do not interpret the intercept.

\(\beta_1\):In this model, for each additional building permits issued, the monthly sales of drywall increases by 476.3 (assuming the other variables are held constant).

\(\beta_2\):In this model, for each additional percentage point in five-year mortgage rate, the monthly sales of drywall increases by 1698.8 (assuming the other variables are held constant).

\(\beta_3\):In this model, for each additional percentage point in vacancy rate in apartments, the monthly sales of drywall decreases by 1052.8 (assuming the other variables are held constant).

\(\beta_4\):In this model, for each additional percentage point in vacancy rate in office buildings, the monthly sales of drywall increases by 130.8 (assuming the other variables are held constant).

F Test

\[H_0: \beta_1 = \beta_2 = \beta_3 = 0\] \(H_1\): One or both of the parameters is not equal to zero.

cat("Since p-value of F test =  0.1979 > 0.05, there is no sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis. All of the beta_i are equal to zero. Thus, none of the independent variable is not linearly related to y. This regression model is invalid.")
## Since p-value of F test =  0.1979 > 0.05, there is no sufficient evidence to reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis. All of the beta_i are equal to zero. Thus, none of the independent variable is not linearly related to y. This regression model is invalid.

t Test \[H_0: \beta_i = 0\] \[H_0: \beta_i \neq 0\]

## Since p_value of beta2 =0.0427 < 0.05, with 95% confidence, we conclude  that there is enough evidence to infer that weekly expenditures on newspaper advertising is linearly related to the weekly gross sales;however,there is no enough evidence to conclude that each of the following variables is linearly related to the weekly gross sales: weekly expenditures on direct mailing, expenditures on television commercials.

6. Interpretation

\(\beta_0\):This is the intercept, the value of y when all the variables take the value zero. Since the data range of all the independent variables do not cover the value zero, do not interpret the intercept.

\(\beta_1\):In this model, for each additional $1000 on weekly expenditures on direct mailing, the weekly gross sales increases by 569.9 (assuming the other variables are held constant).

\(\beta_2\):In this model, for each additional $1000 on weekly expenditures on newspaper advertising, the weekly gross sales increases by 3320 (assuming the other variables are held constant).

\(\beta_3\):In this model, for each additional $1000 on weekly expenditures on television commercials, the weekly gross sales increases by 732.2 (assuming the other variables are held constant).

2. Propose a statistical model

Suppose that number of years of education (in year) (x1), age (in year)(x2), tnumber of children (count)(x3), personal income (in thousands of dollars)(x4) and the error\(\epsilon\) by the following regression model: \[y = \beta_0 + \beta_1x_1 + \beta_2x_2 + \beta_3x_3 + \beta_4x_4 + \epsilon \] y = amount spent on lottery tickets as a percentage of total household income (in percentage point). x1 = number of years of education (in year). x2 = age (in year). x3 = number of children (count), x4 = personal income (in thousands of dollars). ε = error variable.
